$I = (10 \times 7 \times \frac{3}{2}) = 105$

$\text{Total Amount} = 1000 + 105 = 1105$
+++

</md></sn><sn><md>### 03.Determination of Rate of Profit {.text-center}

**Equation and Fact** :

- **rate of profit** $r=\frac{I}{pn} \times 100$ ( percentage form )

- **principal and profit of two different times given** <br>
Principal + Profit in $n_2$ years = $T_2$ Tk<br>
Principal + Profit in $n_1$ years = $T_1$ Tk<br>
$\text{Profit in } (n_2-n_1)\text{ years} = T_2-T_1$ Where $T_2&gt;T_1$<br>
Since the principal remains fixed, the increase in the total amount represents the profit earned during $(n_2-n_1)$ years.<br>
$\text{Profit in 1 year} = \frac{T_2-T_1}{n_2-n_1}$<br>
**Note:** $T_2-T_1$ is the additional amount accumulated between years $n_1$ and $n_2$. Since this increase was earned over $(n_2-n_1)$ years, dividing by the number of years gives the profit earned in one year

- **Both principal have same rate of profit** <br>
$P_1$ tk for $n_1$ years and $P_2$ tk for $n_2$ give total profit T tk.If rate of profit in both cases are equal what is the rate of profit ?<br>
$I_1 + I_2 = T$<br>
$P_1rn_1 + P_2rn_2 = T$<br>
$r = ..$


**Type of Math** :
- IPn given
- profit-principal given instead of profit
- profit and principal given of two different time
- both principal have same rate


